# The example package must survive git BYTE-FOR-BYTE.
#
# Every file below is covered by a hash that is itself committed inside the
# verdict: the per-file `files_sha256` map, the evidence `content_hash`, the
# ruleset content hash inside the `verdict_hash`. These files carry CRLF line
# endings exactly as they were emitted, and git's end-of-line normalization
# (`core.autocrlf`, `text=auto`) would rewrite them to LF on checkout —
# silently changing the bytes and breaking every one of those hashes for
# anyone who clones the repository.
#
# `-text` disables all EOL conversion for this subtree. Do not remove it, and
# do not "tidy" the line endings of these files: the whole point of the
# example is that what was evaluated is what is published.
* -text
